 A fundamental challenge in matching markets is that participants must often consider not only their own preferences, but also the preferences of their would-be trading partners. 


For a number of reasons, parties might not be forthcoming about their actual preferences for different kinds of information, perhaps even for the simple reason that communicating preferences can be costly.
For some kinds of preferences---what might call horizontal preferences---there is little to worry about strategically: 
a firm that really wants to hire an economist has no reason to claim they want to hire a sociologist. 

For some kinds of attributes, the other side of the market may

A firm might claim they want the highest quality workers and be willing to pay a premium for those workers. 
Although this might get them more of the ``right'' kind of worker applying, they might also strike a worse wage bargain. 
Furthermore, if the firm's ability to discern ex ante quality is not excellent, they may not get better workers, just more expensive workers. 
At the other end of the market, employers who are quite price sensitive might find that they receive a cheap but adversely selected pool of applicants if they openly declare their preferences.
Faced with this conundrum, employers might counterfactually claim ``average'' tastes in quality, regardless of their true preferences.
In conventional markets, little can be done about this problem, but in computer-mediated markets, the market-making platform can intervene, collecting information from market participants and then communicating it as needed. 



For each job opening, we can compute various quantiles of the profile wages for applicants to that opening. 
For example, if an opening received applicants with profile rates of \$10/hour, \$20/hour and \$30/hour, the median (50th percentile) profile wage would be \$20/hour. 
We can then regress that opening-specific log wage quantile on the employer's choice of tier interacted with the revelation indicator 
\begin{align} \label{eq:pr}
  \log \bar{w}^{PR} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \mbox{ShownPref} + \beta_2 \mbox{MT} + \beta_3 \mbox{HT} + \beta_4 \mbox{(HT $\times$ ShownPref)} + \beta_5 \mbox{(MT $\times$ ShownPref)} + \epsilon
\end{align} 
where $\bar{w}^{PR}$ is the $PR$th percentile of the profile rates of applicants to the job opening. 

