Economists have long-recognized the potential for signaling to overcome market informational problems \citep{spence1973job, crawford1982strategic}. 
With the rise of computer-mediated markets \citep{varian2010computer}, it has become increasingly possible for market-designing platforms to explicitly create signaling opportunities.
However, to date, designed signaling mechanisms have focused on conveying one party's preferences for a particular counter-party~\citep{lee2011propose, coles2013preference}.\footnote{
  For example, with the econ job market signal, sending a signal to a school might indicate the candidate has some geographic preference of special attachment to the school or sees some special match-specific surplus the school might ``miss'' when considering the large number of applications they receive.
}
A more challenging task for platform-designed signaling mechanisms is conveying ``vertical'' preferences, or a buyer's relative preference over price and quality.
With this information, sellers might ``sort'' to the right kind of buyer, potentially reducing search and screening costs and improving match quality. 
However, revealing this information has greater strategic implications, which might preclude an informative separating equilibrium from emerging.

In this paper, we report the results of an attempt to engineer a separating equilibrium in a large online labor market \citep{Horton2010}, via the introduction of a new signaling feature.
With this new mechanism, employers could publicly state their vertical preferences to potential applicants, revealing their relative willingness to pay for ``better'' workers---those with greater experience, ability, expertise, and so on.
%If successful at getting employers more applicants of the right ``type,'' the mechanism would save both workers and employers some of the high search, screening, and application costs that characterize labor markets \citep{rogerson2005search}.

The signaling feature was simple: when posting a job, employers had to select from one of three ``tiers'' to describe the kinds of applicants they were most interested in:
(1) Entry level: ``I am looking for workers with the lowest rates.'';
(2) Intermediate: ``I am looking for a mix of experience and value.'';
(3) Expert: ``I am willing to pay higher rates of the most experienced workers.''
We will refer to these tiers are ``low,'' ``medium,'' and ``high,'' respectively.
When introduced market-wide, this signal would be revealed publicly to all job-seeking workers. 
However, during the experimental phase, not all firms had their signals revealed.
By selectively revealing some signals, we could learn more about the effects of revelation.\footnote{
  We will use the terms ``firm'' and ``employer'' interchangeably. Also, our use of the word employer simple reflects the typical usage of these terms in the literature and is not a comment on the nature of the legal relationship created on the platform. 
} 
Before discussing the experimental design, it is useful to consider what problems an informative signaling equilibrium might solve---but also why such an equilibrium might not be obtainable.

In an informative separating equilibrium, firms interested in the ``best,'' most proven workers would signal ``high'';
firms willing to hire unproven or less able workers (if they are offering a low enough price) would signal ``low.''
Job-seeking workers could then condition their application and bidding decisions on this firm information. 
Despite the usefulness of this preference information to workers, it is unclear whether firms would be willing to make their true preferences public.
Firms must consider the effects of revealing their preferences  on (1) the size and composition of the applicant pool, and (2) the ultimate wage agreed upon with the hired worker.
A firm claiming  ``high'' preferences might get more high quality applicants.
However, those applicants might shade their wage bids up in light of their knowledge about the firm's willingness to pay. 
A firm claiming  ``low'' preferences might get fewer or worse quality applicants, though those applicants are likely to shade their wage bids down.

The relative importance of the applicant pool composition effects and price effects is critical to assessing whether a separating equilibrium in which firms truthfully reveal their type is possible.
If, for example, workers do not ``sort'' but simply tailor bids or bargaining strategies in response to the firm's perceived willingness to pay, then both high and low firms will claim low preferences.
Or if sufficiently few workers are willing to apply to low jobs, low firms will want to claim high preferences.
In either scenario, the outcome is an uninformative pooling equilibrium. 

In light of the many possible paths to failure, the signaling feature was not simply imposed market-wide, but rather was tested experimentally. 
The research questions the experiment was designed to answer focus on the ways an informative signaling equilibrium could fail to materialize when the feature was implemented market wide. 
Our first two research questions focus on the demand side, and are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item whether there is meaningful variation in employer vertical
      preferences not already conveyed by other firm/job opening
      observable attributes; \label{q1}
    \item whether firms are willing to reveal their vertical
      preferences when they know explicitly that workers can condition
      upon this information. \label{q2}
\end{enumerate}     
Our remaining research questions focus on the effects of revelation, namely how revelation affects: 
\begin{enumerate}
  \setcounter{enumi}{2}
\item the composition of applicant pools \label{q3}
\item the size of applicant pools \label{q4}
\item worker wage bidding \label{q5}
\item which workers are hired (if any) and at what terms \label{q6}
\item the ultimate contractual outcomes, such as hours-worked, hired
    worker wages and feedback.\label{q7}
\end{enumerate} 
This admittedly long list of research questions reflects the long list of reasons the signaling mechanism could fail.\footnote{ 
When the feature was introduced, we did not know whether it would ``work,'' and if it did not work, we wanted to have the data to do a credible post-mortem analysis. 
}

Our data comes primarily from an experimental period, in which employers were assigned to different treatment groups.
During the experimental phase, employers were randomized to one of two  arms,  each of which was split into two experimental groups. 
In the ``explicit'' arm of the experiment, employers were told, \emph{ex ante}, that their signal would either be \emph{shown} or \emph{not shown} to applying workers. 
In the ``ambiguous'' arm of the experiment, employers were told the platform \emph{might} reveal their preferences to workers, and then employers were randomized to either have their preferences revealed to would-be job applicants or not, \emph{ex post}.
Any subsequent job opening posted by an employer had the same treatment assignment as the original opening.
However, unless otherwise noted, we only use the first opening posted by the employer. 
We also make limited use of some post-experimental data, with our goal being to assess whether a separating equilibrium persisted once all signals were revealed. 

For research question (\ref{q1})---whether meaningful variation in preferences exist---we find that although stated preferences depend strongly on the category of work (e.g., web development versus data entry), there is still substantial within-category variation. 
Illustrating this cross-category variation, in the ``Administrative Support'' category, \fracLowAdminSpt{}\% employers chose the low tier signal compared, to just \fracLowWeb{}\% in ``Web Development'' making the same choice; in ``Networking \& Information Systems'' the fraction of employers choosing the high tier is \fracHighNetworking{}\%, whereas it is only \fracHighAdminSpt{}\% in ``Administrative Support.''
Despite the evident importance of the job category, there is still substantial within-category variation, with no potential tier signal garnering even close to 100\% of employers.
The residual within-category variation is important, as it implies that the signal \emph{could be} informative to workers and not simply subsumed by other sources of information.

For research question (\ref{q2})---whether buyer \emph{ex ante} knowledge about eventual revelation affects signal choice---we find that it does not.
Using data from the explicit arm of the experiment, we find that almost exactly the same fractions of employers choose the different tiers, seemingly independent of whether their preferences would be revealed.
Of course, there could be some hidden sorting that left fractions unchanged while changing the composition of employers, but we have no evidence that this was the case.
It is also possible that this lack of conditioning was a short-run result, in that neither employers nor workers yet understood the implications of signaling, or that the long-run market equilibrium was different from what was implied by the experimental results. 
However, after market-wide implementation, we find no evidence of a change in the fractions of employers selecting the various tiers many months later.

For research question (\ref{q3})---the effects of revelation on application pool composition---we want to know if workers direct applications to employers of the appropriate type.
For this analysis, we use the  ``ambiguous arm'' of the experiment, in which employers were told that the platform \emph{might} reveal their preferences to workers, with actual revelation determined at random, \emph{ex post}. 
Because employers did not know \emph{ex ante} whether their signal would be revealed, we can treat their signal as exogenous, allowing us to see how revelation of the signal affected outcomes, holding the tier selection fixed.
Namely, we can compare the characteristics and behavior of the applicant pool when the signal was revealed to when it was not, by signal type.

We find that workers strongly respond to the signals sent by employers.
Among employers signaling high preferences, those having their preferences revealed to would-be applicants received applicants that were about 5-10\% more experienced (depending on the measure of experience). 
Employers signaling medium preferences received about the same applicant pool, regardless of revelation.
Employers signaling low preferences received applicants with substantially less experience, with reductions in past experience of about 10-15\%.

For research question (\ref{q4})---whether revelation affects the size of applicant pools---we find some evidence that it does, though the effects are modest.
Overall, pooled across all three tiers, we find about a 5\% reduction in the size of the applicant pool, with this drop largely accounted for by a substantial drop in applicants to low tier openings.
There is no drop in the number of applicants to medium tier openings, and perhaps some evidence of an increase in applications to high tier openings.
However, this evidence of a increase in the high tier is somewhat belied by an analysis of the full sample (including both arms), which suggests if anything, the count of applicants to high tier openings also declined.\footnote{ 
  Changes in applicant pool size raise the question of whether these were anticipated by bidding workers and incorporated into bids.
  For example, if workers knew the employer would face a smaller applicant pool, applying worker might bid up or vice versa if they knew the employer would face a larger pool.
  However, we find that this consideration can largely be ignored by workers, at least with respect to the optimal wage bid.
  Using day-to-day variation in applicant pool sizes, we find that workers make little adjustment in response to these fluctuations.
  To give a sense of the magnitudes, for low tier job openings, we found that revelation reduced the pool size by about 5\%---which we predict would cause the average worker to increase their bid, ceteris paribus, by less than 1/2 of 1\%. 
}

For research question (\ref{q5})---whether revelation affected applicant wage bidding---we find that workers strongly condition their wage bids on the employer's revealed signal.
For high tier employers, revelation of the signal increased the wage bids they received by 10\%.
For medium tier employers, there was no detectable effect, while for low tier employers, revelation lowered wage bids by 15\%.

As revelation affected the composition of applicant pools, we would expect wage bids to be higher in high tier openings and lower in low tier openings.  
However, the change in bids we observe was not due solely to compositional changes.
Using the fact that workers send multiple applications, we show that \emph{within} workers, there is direct conditioning on the revealed signal---the same worker bids more when they know they are facing a employer with ``higher'' vertical preferences.
Furthermore, we present evidence that shading in wage bids was not due to perceived job amenities/disamenties that might correlated with the employer tier, but rather that workers were considering employer willingness to pay directly.

For research question (\ref{q6})---whether revelation affected hiring and the composition of hired workers---we find little change in the level of hiring, but large effects on the composition of hired workers. 
The main composition effect was for substantially less experienced workers to be hired by low tier employers:
hired workers had about 12\% less experience and about 18\% lower past hourly earnings when the signal was revealed.
There is little compositional change from revelation in the other tiers, at least with respect to observable worker attributes.
However, as we will discuss later, there is some evidence of better matches in the high tier following revelation.
In terms of the wages of hired workers, in both the medium and high tiers, wages were 6\% higher following revelation, and about 10\% lower in the low tier. 

For research question (\ref{q7})---the ultimate contractual outcomes---ideally, we would have enough power to only use the ambiguous arm for this analysis.
However, given that not all job openings are filled, and that some measures of interest, such as hours-worked are high variance, we do not have enough power when only using the ambiguous arm to make strong claims. 
As such, we pool observations from both the ambiguous and explicit arms and treat signal selection as exogenous.
As noted earlier, in the explicit arm, the treatment \emph{could} have affected tier selection, though there is no evidence that it did.
We also use all job openings by employers to increase the sample size, but clustering by employer to account for the now-nested structure of the data. 

We find that overall, hours-worked increased, as did the total wage bill.
Hours-worked increased by about 5\% and the total wage bill by about 3\%.
These increases occurred in every tier. 
An increase in hours-worked is unsurprising in the low-tier, given the lower wages. 
However, an increase in hours-worked in the high-tier is surprising: 
hired workers in the high tier had nearly 5\% higher wages despite not being \emph{observably} more productive, and yet we observe more hours-worked.
At higher wages, firms should economize on labor, and yet if anything, they demanded more hours.
A reconciliation is that revelation lead to better matches, and so despite the higher wage, employers demanded more hours.
One counter-argument to this ``more hours, better matches'' argument is that with higher wages, workers have an incentive work more hours, stretch out tasks and pad hours. 
However, this seems unlikely, as we also find that employers who had their signal revealed---and hence were paying higher wages but also buying more hours---gave higher feedback to the worker and to the platform.
Furthermore, on the platform, employers have extensive tools to monitor and cap hours-worked, suggesting we should think of employers as choosing the number of hours. 

To the extent these measures are reasonable proxies for employer surplus, it seems likely that match quality improved. 
Although there are no theoretical guarantees that a separating equilibrium is preferable, in this platform, the results are consistent with the platform goals:
employers got more of the right kinds of applicants and seemed to form better matches. 

The key contribution of this paper is to show how a platform can change the market equilibrium with an engineered signaling mechanism.
Workers were clearly not fully informed about seller preferences, as they altered their application behavior and bidding when they could condition on the new information created by this mechanism.
The evidence suggests the introduction of the signaling mechanism improved match quality.
Furthermore, it likely helped inexperienced workers target the kinds of employers that would actually be willing to hire them.
Overall, we have some evidence that the mechanism lowered search costs by reducing pool sizes.
All of this was achieved for a feature that has de minimus marginal costs.

In terms of generality, the kind of problem this signaling mechanism addresses is commonplace in markets.
Relatively few markets are characterized by fully-formed preferences and centralized match-making.
This can be seen in the growing interest in how preferences are learned in matching markets \citep{acemoglu2017, ashlagi2017communication}.
Many more markets require buyers and sellers seek each other out, initiating contact with potential partners and then deciding whether to match in a decentralized fashion.
In these markets, both sides engage in costly search and must weigh the attributes of the other side against the proposed terms---a key market design challenge is lowering these costs.
As more of economic life becomes computer-mediated \citep{varian2010computer}, introducing signaling mechanisms is likely to be an important tool in the market designer ``toolbox.''
The ``design pattern'' illustrated in this paper can be applied to many kinds of marketplaces---platforms can take some dimension on which buyers and sellers differ and attributes and then offering the two sides structured ways to send and receive such signals. 


\subsection{Direct evidence of sorting} 
The effects of revelation on applicant pool composition implies that workers are conditioning on the signal when deciding which job openings to apply to.
As workers often send multiple applications, many workers applied to job openings where preferences were observable and those were they were not.
If revealing preferences allowed for more targeted application, then we should see less dispersion in the vertical preference of the applied-to opening when preferences are revealed compared to when they are not.

A simple measure of application dispersion is the variance in the associated tier when it is re-coded as -1, 0, and 1 for low, medium and high, respectively.
For each worker, we compute the variance in applications to $\textsc{ShownPref} = 1$ job openings and $\textsc{ShownPref} = 0$ job openings.
We then use that variance as an outcome, restricting the same to those workers that applied to equal numbers of jobs in both experimental groups. 

